A good bit of tension in Raised by Humans comes from the fact that a man is unlikely to get the paperwork to adopt a child, more so if that child is female, even more so if they are not legally in the adoption system.
All that is on top of the human-anthro social divide that seems to exist in the story.

In a reversed story, the anthro wouldn't have to worry about the paperwork nearly as much.
She'd still have to deal with the human-anthro divide though.
However, that tension is dwarfed by the fear of having your loved one dragged away from you by the government and them being discarded into a terrible environment.
